<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="476" pageId="4" pageNumber="475" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1893,2026]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,151,933]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="476" pageId="4" pageNumber="475">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1965,1990]" pageId="4" pageNumber="475">Description.</emphasis>
Adult (
<figureCitation box="[439,509,1965,1990]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 10" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1870,1893]" captionTargetBox="[200,1377,193,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[187,1392,193,1828]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 10. Adults of Kiwaia (Empista) spp. 1, K. (E.) dryosyrta (Meyrick), HT, ♂ (India); 2, K. (E.) p. palaearctica (Povolný), HT, ♂ (Nepal); 3, K. (E.) p. palaearctica (Povolný), ♂ (Nepal); 4, K. (E.) p. palaearctica (Povolný), ♂ (Nepal); 5, K. (E.) p. secunda (Povolný), HT, ♂ (Nepal; 6, K. (E.) mengdana sp. n., HT, ♂ (China: Qinghai); 7, K. (E.) kostjuki (Povolný), HT, ♂ (Russia: Zabaikalskyi krai); 8, K. (E.) kostjuki (Povolný), ♀ (China: Hebei); 9, K. (E.) kostjuki (China: Hebei); 10, K. (E.) nyingchiensis sp. n., HT, ♂ (China: Xizang)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265643/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="475">
Fig. 
<number box="[495,509,1966,1990]" pageId="4" pageNumber="475" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
): Wingspan 16.0 mm. Head brown, frons ligh-brown to grey; labial palpus up curved, brown motled with black, inner surface of segment 
<number box="[851,865,2002,2026]" pageId="4" pageNumber="475" value="2.0">2</number>
lighter, segment 
<number box="[1070,1084,2002,2026]" pageId="4" pageNumber="475" value="3.0">3</number>
about 1.5 times narrower and shorter than segment 
<number box="[404,419,152,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476" value="3.0">3</number>
, acute; scapus black, other segments brown with grey rings; thorax and tegulae black; forewing dark, brown to black, black scales concentrated mainly along costal and dorsal margins, central area of forewing slightly ligther, mottled with grey and brown; indistinct four black dots in cell; diffuse grey subapical fascia on 
<number box="[258,271,260,284]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476" value="3.0">3</number>
/ 
<number box="[281,297,260,284]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476" value="4.0">4</number>
; cilia grey black-tipped; hindwing dark grey.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,933]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[375,459,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 28 – 35" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1851,1874]" captionTargetBox="[199,1384,209,1809]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[171,1407,193,1821]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 28 – 35. Male genitalia of Kiwaia (Empista) spp. 28, K. (E.) dryosyrta (Meyrick), HT (India), slide J. F. G. C. 8252; 29, K. (E.) p. secunda (Povolný), HT (Nepal), slide Jp. 4834; 30, K. (E.) p. palaearctica (Povolný), HT (Nepal), slide Mn. 3112, ZSM 1092; 31, K. (E.) p. palaearctica (Povolný) (Nepal), slide no. 22746; 32, K. (E.) mengdana sp. n., HT (China: Qinghai), slide no. L 95446; 33, K. (E.) kostjuki (Povolný), HT (Russia: Zabaikalskyi krai), slide Bdz. 31; 34, K. (E.) kostjuki (Povolný), PT (Russia: Zabaikalskyi krai), slide (without number); 35, K. (E.) kostjuki (Povolný) (China: Hebei), prep. in glycerol (= slide no. OB 7 / 14)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265646/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">
Fig. 
<number box="[427,459,296,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476" value="28.0">28</number>
</figureCitation>
): Uncus prolonged, weakly narrowed apically, posterior margin rounded; gnathos long, evenly curved, sickle-shaped; tegumen comparatively long with deep anteromedial emargination; valva weakly curved, about of equal width, weakly dilated apically, reaching the top of uncus; sacculus narrow, tapered, weakly curved, about 
<number box="[321,331,404,428]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[343,357,404,428]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476" value="3.0">3</number>
as long as valva; tegumen slightly broader than long, posteromedial emargination broadly rounded; vincular processes broadly rounded, shorter than sacculus, separated from sacculus by broad gap; saccus moderately broad, tapered apically; phallus curved at abtuse ungle, caecum weakly inflated, distal portion sclerotised along one margin and terminated in short tooth, apical arm big, down-curved.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,933]" box="[199,400,548,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">Female unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="476" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,933]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,583,608]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">Remarks.</emphasis>
The species is similar externally to 
<taxonomicName box="[735,963,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Empista" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="476" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palaearctica" subGenus="Empista">
<emphasis box="[735,762,585,608]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">K.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[780,804,585,608]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">E.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[822,963,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">palaearctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the head is lighter, the forewing are broader and darker. As far as one can judge from the lateral view the male genitalia look somewhat similar to those of 
<taxonomicName box="[186,418,655,680]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Empista" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="476" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palaearctica" subGenus="Empista">
<emphasis box="[186,212,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">K.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[232,256,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">E.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[277,418,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">palaearctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having narrow tapered sacculus, but the vincular processes are rounded rather than pointed, and the apical arm of the phallus is larger and differs in the shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1165,727,752]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,933]" box="[199,1165,727,752]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,727,752]" pageId="5" pageNumber="476">Biology.</emphasis>
